headline: Senior Computer Science Student

bio:
I am a Robotics Engineering student at Arizona State University with a minor in Business Administration, combining technical engineering skills with an understanding of strategy, operations, and organizational management. I enjoy building real world technology that solves practical problems, from autonomous systems and IoT platforms to full stack software tools used in live operational environments.

Alongside my engineering work, I serve as a Building Manager Supervisor at ASU, where I lead teams, manage large scale facilities, and design systems that improve efficiency and accountability. I have built production level tools using Arduino, MongoDB, Python, and barcode based systems to support thousands of events and daily operations.

My business background allows me to think beyond just technical design and consider cost, scalability, user needs, and long term impact. I am especially interested in the intersection of robotics, software, and entrepreneurship, where innovative technology meets real world deployment. I am always looking for opportunities to learn, build, and contribute to high impact projects.

projects.title: Inventory Logger
projects.description: Created a full-stack inventory management system for the Arizona State University Memorial Union Operations Team. The tool streamlines equipment check-in/check-out, tracks item history, manages client tabling reservations, assigns rooms and tables, automates issue reporting, and generates detailed logs for administrators. Features include barcode/QR scanning, role-based dashboards, mobile-optimized scanning mode, monthly inventory check workflows, system logs, verification logs, and integration with Google Sheets and email notifications. Built with React, Node.js/Express, MongoDB, and JWT authentication.

projects.title: TerraGuard
projects.description: TerraGuard is an autonomous rover designed to help firefighters and fire-watch teams detect early wildfire risks in remote areas. The system uses environmental sensors, GPS, and a live camera to monitor temperature, smoke, and air quality, sending real-time data and alerts over a secure wireless network. I worked on embedded hardware integration, microcontroller programming, and system wiring to help build a rugged, field-ready wildfire response platform.

work.title: Building Manager
work.description: As a Building Manager at Arizona State University’s Memorial Union and Student Pavilion, I supported daily operations for a 290,000-square-foot facility hosting over 10,000 events and 4 million visitors annually. I provided on-site event and AV support, managed room setups and turnovers, and handled guest concerns, safety issues, and emergency situations in real time. I worked closely with maintenance, dining services, event coordinators, and external vendors to ensure smooth operations, while monitoring building conditions, equipment use, and overall facility readiness to maintain a safe, professional, and welcoming environment.

work.title: Building Manager Supervisor
work.description: After being promoted to Building Manager Supervisor, I led and coordinated a team of approximately 20 Building Managers, overseeing scheduling, shift coverage, and operational execution across high-volume events and daily facility operations. I organized and led team meetings and area briefings, developed training materials, operational guides, and onboarding resources, and facilitated training to ensure staff were prepared to handle customer service, safety, and technical responsibilities. I served as the primary escalation point for complex guest issues, emergencies, and facility incidents, while also coordinating with university departments and external agencies. In addition, I designed and implemented a barcode-based inventory management system using a MongoDB backend to improve equipment tracking, accountability, and data reliability across the department.

work.title: Senior Sales Specialist
work.description: As a Senior Sales Specialist at the Apple Store, I delivered personalized customer experiences by matching customers with the right Apple products and services while supporting high-volume store operations. I analyzed sales trends and customer demand and worked closely with Apple’s HQ marketing team to help optimize product placement, promotions, and sales strategies. I also supported and mentored other specialists on the floor to drive consistent performance and customer satisfaction.

projects.title: APCSP Wordle App
projects.description: I took AP Computer Science Principles (APCSP) during my second semester of freshman year and got a 5 on the AP exam. I built a Wordle APP in order to submit for the project aspect of the AP CSP Exam. I coded the whole application in Javascript in Code.org. My goal was to entertain users by creating a guessing game where the user tries to guess the randomly-generated five-letter word. I learned a lot about Javascript throughout the second semester and this project was a great way to showcase the skills I learned. I also learned how to think more critically and logically whenever I was stuck on a problem.

projects.title: HSC Composting Bag, An Adaptable and Flexible Solution
projects.description: My HSC Group (Gabi, Ethan, and Minha) brainstormed, planned, developed, built, and tested a sturdy and environmentally friendly composter that is more efficient and durable than others, is easy to navigate even for the novice, and can withstand a wide range of temperatures. We placed 1st at PVSEF and 3rd at AZSEF under the category "Earth & Environmental Sciences". I learned more about each phase of the Engineering Design process by applying it in a more application based context and developing a successful capstone project. I also learned more about the importance of collaboration and communication in a group project environment setting, which is essential for fostering success within the workplace.

projects.title: Carpooling Application
projects.description: My partner Ashwath and I coded a carpooling application for our final project in AP CSA. We coded the whole application in Java and Javascript/HTML/CSS in IntelliJ. Our goal was to design, build, and test a community-based carpooling application for community members that will leverage real-time data and an efficient matching algorithm to connect people who have similar routes and schedules, optimizing travel efficiency and reducing individual commuting impacts. My role in the project was to code the front-end Google Maps aspect of the application. I learned a lot about API Keys, specifically Google Maps API, and how to use them within a programming application. I also learned about the JSON framework for Java so that the coder can render and display screens to the user.

projects.title: Animal Rescue Networking Platform
projects.description: My partner Aarohi and I coded an application that expands opportunities for people to get involved in wildlife rehabilitation, which allows them to take part in preserving nature and wildlife around them and increase an animal’s chance of survival. We coded the whole application using REACT in VSCode. After finishing this capstone project, we learned a lot about Google Maps API, node.js, and REACT's capabilities in javascript.

projects.title: AI Icebreakers App
projects.description:
As freshmen at ASU, we realized how common awkward silences can be when meeting new people. Our solution: an AI-powered listener that detects about 10 seconds of silence and then suggests context-aware prompts based on the ongoing conversation and previous topics.

● Dhruva Aher and I built the Front-End using Python Flet
● Prince Zerubbabel Solomon and I developed the Back-End using Python libraries, Google Gemini API, and Supermemory API for voice recognition + text-to-speech

projects.title: HoneyComb Propellor Maintenence System
projects.description: The 2025 theme — “The Incredible [Turbo] Machine: Engines and Power Systems of Tomorrow” — pushed us to think creatively and engineer practical solutions. Our project idea is to build a conceptual autonomous system paired witha robot to fully automate the swapping of the propeller compression system. The propeller compression systems operate like a Stack Data Structure, following a Last-In-First-Out algorithm. This makes the propellers in the back very tedious and time-consuming to fix since it would require taking all the propeller systems in the front. Thus, we conceptually designed a robot, a claw, and a chamber that would detect and fix when needed.

projects.title: Map LED Population Representation
projects.description:
As part of the Theta Tau at Arizona State University semester-long pledging process, my pledge class, Chi Gamma, was tasked with a semester-long project that would benefit the Engineering Fraternity and incorporate all of our pledge members' majors.

As a result, one of our pledge brothers, Sydney Braun, brainstormed the idea of creating a wooden map that would display the number of active members, potential new members (PNMs), and alumni from each state/country as of Fall 2025, represented by different-colored LED lights.✨

This group project satisfied the three pillars of Theta Tau:
👫Brotherhood: Showed where each brother came from and how Theta Tau has brought all of us students together as a family! Additionally, working on this project strengthened my bond with my PNM brothers!
👔Professionalism: The whole woodworking process required professional project management principles: project management & workflow, precision and quality control, collaborative problem-solving, and role specialization.
🌳Service: We recycled and reused many of the project components, especially wood, metal, and wiring.

projects.title: LaundryLens
projects.description:
Our final project theme was "Perceiving the World Through Technology," and we were tasked to create a prototype of a wearable, noninvasive, fashionable, and portable product/device focused on alleviating pain points in the daily life activities of a vision-impaired person.

 My team consisted of 6 members: Prince Zerubbabel Solomon, Dhruva Aher, Piotr Jandura, Natalia Piatek, David (Davey) Nearman, and me (Ethan Nguyen). Together, we brainstormed and developed a prototype that would specifically help visually impaired people sort their laundry, titled "LaundryLens." It's a pair of glasses that, when held at an optimal distance, the user can press a button to capture an image of the clothing article, and it will then provide audible feedback on the type of clothing article, its color, and its pattern.

projects.title: Unified Chest X-ray Model
projects.description: Created a generalized vision transformer on unified chest x-ray architecture using pytorch. The model was trained on various diverse datasets (MIMC, ChestX-Det, NODE21, TBX11) and able to identify disease presence, perform disease localization, disease semantic segmentation, X-ray orientation. This model applied transfer learning context so that learning was shared across various tasks. This model outperformed standard vision transformers (DINO, DETR) trained independently on each dataset for all tasks.

projects.title: Markov chain + game theory simulation
projects.description: Simulated a round-robin tournament of AI agents where each game consisted of a repeated sequence of zero-sum games, and the winner of said tournament is the number of points made. Each AI agent's behaivor was recorded by a transition matrix, and that transition matrix was used to generate a markov model to observe longterm behaivor.
